               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WOOD</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-600" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-600" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-600" type="surname" value="MENDEZ"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-600" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH MENDEZ</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a clothier at 142, High-street, Woolwich—on 17th February, about 2 in the day, the prisoner came into my shop for a pair of boots, and I said I had none to suit him, as I was in a hurry to go, and I left the shop—this is my coat (<hi rend="italic">produced.</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I was in Deptford all that day, I was not in your shop at all. <hi rend="italic">Witness</hi>. He is the person—he is rather paralysed—I can swear to him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-601" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-601" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-601" type="surname" value="MENDEZ"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-601" type="given" value="REBECCA"></interp>REBECCA MENDEZ</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's daughter—on 17th February 1 hung two coats on the inside of our shop—the prisoner came in between 3 and 4 on that day, and asked if I had a coat and waistcoat to sell him—I shoved him one at 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—he said it was too dear, and I put it on the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186504100185"></xptr>
               <p>shelf again—I saw the two coats that were afterwards missed, hanging up in the shop while the prisoner was there—he did not purchase anything—he asked me if there was anybody at home, and I said no—some information was given to me between 6 and 7 by Mr. Prior, and I found the coats were gone.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-602" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-602" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-602" type="surname" value="PRIOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-602" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN PRIOR</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 28, Artillery-place, Woolwich, and am an eating house keeper—on 17th February I saw the prisoner standing at Mendez's door—I went next door to speak to a party, and presently I saw the prisoner come away from the shop into the road putting a coat on—that coat has not been found—it was not this one—I think it was a frock coat—I could not see, because it was dark—I saw him ran away, and I went to the shop—I am positive the prisoner is the man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-603" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-603" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-603" type="surname" value="BORER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-603" type="given" value="MARTHA"></interp>MARTHA BORER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of James Borer, of 90, High-street, Woolwich—on 17th February the prisoner came to my shop just upon 6 in the evening, with this coat on, and asked me if I would purchase it—I said, you must give me your name and address—he said, "My name is Thomas Sutton, and I have just come in from Gravesend, and I am going to lodge at Uncle Tom's, I have bought my bed there"—I then bought the coat of him for 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—about a fortnight afterwards the prisoner came and said, "Have you got a coat to sell, I should like to buy that pilot coat I sold to you some time ago"—I said by way of excuse, "You shall have the coat, "and I sent for Mr. Mendez—I saw a policeman passing and called him in—I had received some information—I afterwards showed him this coat and he identified it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> Can you swear I was the man who came to your shop? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, positively.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18650410-name-604" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-604" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-604" type="surname" value="HICKMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18650410-name-604" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT HICKMAN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, R</hi> 172). I was called in, and took the prisoner into custody—I asked him where he got the coat from—he said he had bought it—I asked him who from—he said he did not know—he said, "Don't take me into custody, I will pay the 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. back"—he gave his name as John Smith—I found a discharge from the army on him, with the name of Sutton on it—I asked him if that was his name and he said, "Yes"</p>
